We currently use SVN (although we pry should change to Git, because of the
branching/mergin limitations of SVN)

We have 3 major branches:
/httpdocs/trunk
/httpdocs/branches/stable
- descended from trunk
- only contains changes deemed stable enough for actual use
/httpdocs/branches/production
- descended from 'stable'
- only contains changes that are ready to be deployed
- does not contain certain test, database reset, and doc files, for security
  reasons

SVN merging is much trickier than it appears on the surface.  There are many
edge cases which don't work as expected.  Consult the SVN documentation before
performing any merges.

In general, when you merge a descendant branch back into a parent (i.e.,
merging 'production' into 'stable'), you must use the --reintegrate tag.
Afterwards, you must block the change on the reintegrated branch so that it
will still work.  See:
http://svnbook.red-bean.com/nightly/en/svn.branchmerge.advanced.html#svn.branchmerge.advanced.reintegratetwice
